WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.760
 Now it is time to start building a little more complex machine language, assembly language, applications.

00:00:06.760 --> 00:00:10.440
 And as always, these slides are not necessarily the best reference.

00:00:10.440 --> 00:00:19.000
 Once you listen to them, you should probably start looking at the online documentation that I provide for the CDC 6504.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:21.660
 So we'll start with another review of the architecture.

00:00:21.660 --> 00:00:24.400
 By now, this should be pretty familiar to you.

00:00:24.400 --> 00:00:30.400
 We have a program counter, which is telling us where in the instruction memory to retrieve the next instruction.

00:00:30.400 --> 00:00:34.200
 We have the accumulated register, which is kind of the most flexible register.

00:00:34.200 --> 00:00:40.460
 We have the Z and the N flags that tells whether last thing we did in a register was zero or negative or a compare instruction.

00:00:40.460 --> 00:00:46.100
 The X and the Y registers are registers that are a little less capable than the accumulator.

00:00:46.100 --> 00:00:53.860
 We show instruction memory in base two and data memory we show in hex because it usually contains ASCII.

00:00:53.860 --> 00:00:59.240
 So there is a new thing that's only in assembly labels or something that's only in assembly.

00:00:59.240 --> 00:01:02.800
 And this data directive is the thing that's only in assembly.

00:01:02.800 --> 00:01:13.300
 Everything we've done so far in the assembler is populating the instruction memory by parsing the instruction, the assembly language instructions and producing the zeros and ones that are the machine language.

00:01:13.300 --> 00:01:21.300
 But there's also this thing called a data directive where we can fill the data memory up with some pre before the program starts, we load.

00:01:21.300 --> 00:01:29.200
 There's an act called loading. We load the program into the memory, load the instruction memory, and we can preload the data memory with this data directive.

00:01:29.200 --> 00:01:38.260
 But it's not machine code. It is something that assemblers do and give us a loadable image that includes a data segment, basically.

00:01:38.260 --> 00:01:42.600
 And it can either be a quoted string or a series of hex digits.

00:01:42.600 --> 00:01:55.300
 And we mostly will use quoted strings so you can print hello world by having a single line of machine language break, which means halt, but then have the data filled with hello world.

00:01:55.300 --> 00:01:58.700
 And it just turns out that the emulator dumps out the data when it's all done.

00:01:58.700 --> 00:02:02.200
 So this is the simplest program.

00:02:02.200 --> 00:02:08.600
 It's not really machine language, but it's the simplest program in the emulator to make it print hello world.

00:02:08.600 --> 00:02:16.500
 So here's just a couple. So in this one, we're going to add 27 plus 15 and then store it in memory location zero.

00:02:16.500 --> 00:02:21.500
 So we load 27, an immediate, immediate constant into the accumulator.

00:02:21.500 --> 00:02:25.100
 Then we add 15, which is another immediate constant.

00:02:25.100 --> 00:02:29.700
 So that's 42. And then we're going to store that in location memory location zero.

00:02:29.700 --> 00:02:32.300
 So you can see by that. And then we halt.

00:02:32.300 --> 00:02:40.800
 So by the time the program counter makes 0, 0, 5 hex, there is a single 0x2a, which is 42 in hex.

00:02:40.800 --> 00:02:49.000
 And then you can see that that prints out asterisk, because if you go look at your ASCII chart, asterisk is 42 decimal.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:52.500
 Our next example is just printing hello.

00:02:52.500 --> 00:03:00.900
 And so we're going to end up putting this in memory so that the program will dump out the memory, starting at memory location zero after the program finishes.

00:03:00.900 --> 00:03:05.300
 So we do an immediate load of the letter H and we start in memory location zero.

00:03:05.300 --> 00:03:09.200
 We do an immediate load of the letter E and store that in location one.

00:03:09.200 --> 00:03:13.000
 We do immediate load of the letter L and store that in location two.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:16.100
 And then we store that again in location three because there's two L's.

00:03:16.100 --> 00:03:22.400
 And then we do an immediate load of the letter O and we store that in location four and then we quit.

00:03:22.400 --> 00:03:26.600
 And then if you look at the memory, there is H-E-L-L-O in the memory in hex.

00:03:26.600 --> 00:03:30.300
 And then you can see that the program prints hello out when it's all done.

00:03:30.300 --> 00:03:36.000
 And again, this is just exploring some assembly language slash machine language.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:42.500
 So now we're going to do a little more complicated and a little more practical example.

00:03:42.500 --> 00:03:48.700
 So we are going to uppercase a whole string of characters and we're going to take the characters from memory,

00:03:48.700 --> 00:03:55.200
 read them all from memory in a loop, check them, convert them to uppercase and then store them back if necessary.

00:03:55.200 --> 00:04:03.500
 So the key to this is our data is going to be preloaded using the data directive in memory locations zero through four.

00:04:03.500 --> 00:04:07.000
 And that's the hello with the H uppercased already.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:12.000
 So now we've run it. You can see the status is halted and you see that it printed out an uppercase hello.

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:21.300
 And the only real thing that it changed was memory location one, two, three and four are now the uppercase versions of those letters.

00:04:21.300 --> 00:04:27.700
 Now, before we go through that code in some detail, let's think about uppercasing this string in other languages.

00:04:27.700 --> 00:04:31.100
 Now, if you're a Python person, you'd be like hello dot upper.

00:04:31.100 --> 00:04:33.200
 There's a method. Hello.

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:37.400
 The string is an object and you can call a method dot upper.

00:04:37.400 --> 00:04:40.500
 Now, it's not changing the hello to upper.

00:04:40.500 --> 00:04:43.000
 It is just giving you a copy of that.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:47.300
 Now, if we didn't have upper, we would have some pretty ugly Python.

00:04:47.300 --> 00:04:51.200
 So we couldn't you can't change a Python string in place.

00:04:51.200 --> 00:04:53.600
 So you have to take and make a variable.

00:04:53.600 --> 00:04:56.200
 In this case, I'll call it mem because it's like the memory.

00:04:56.200 --> 00:04:58.500
 But you can't change memory in Python.

00:04:58.500 --> 00:05:00.400
 You got to make a new one.

00:05:00.400 --> 00:05:10.400
 So then we're going to have this for loop for XR, which kind of is my way of saying X X register is range len of mem.

00:05:10.400 --> 00:05:19.100
 That's zero. That's going to run XR through zero through four up to but not including five.

00:05:19.100 --> 00:05:24.700
 And then we're going to retrieve memory one character of memory from XR to XR plus one.

00:05:24.700 --> 00:05:26.400
 Put that in the accumulator.

00:05:26.400 --> 00:05:32.800
 And if the accumulator is greater than or equal to A and less than or equal to Z,

00:05:32.800 --> 00:05:39.300
 which is between A and Z inclusive, then we're going to compute the new character.

00:05:39.300 --> 00:05:42.800
 And now you'll see this CHR and ORD.

00:05:42.800 --> 00:05:47.100
 And the problem is, is that in Python, we're not even using ASCII.

00:05:47.100 --> 00:05:48.900
 The hello is Unicode.

00:05:48.900 --> 00:05:54.900
 So ORD says, give me the ordinal of the current character I'm looking at, ACC.

00:05:54.900 --> 00:05:59.500
 Subtract the ordinal of lowercase a and add the ordinal uppercase a.

00:05:59.500 --> 00:06:06.000
 Now, this wouldn't necessarily work for any set of characters because Unicode can have a lot of things.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:11.600
 And so the actual uppercase is a little more complex inside of Python.

00:06:11.600 --> 00:06:17.600
 So we've computed the uppercase character if we know it's a lowercase character by mathematics.

00:06:17.600 --> 00:06:24.300
 And then we append it to the new version of the memory, building that up one string at a time.

00:06:24.300 --> 00:06:26.100
 And then we print it out.

00:06:26.100 --> 00:06:34.400
 And so you can't even do this because Python is not really designed for low-level array-like things.

00:06:34.400 --> 00:06:36.200
 Lists are not arrays.

00:06:36.200 --> 00:06:42.500
 Although if you took my C programming class, you would understand that they're kind of arrays, okay?

00:06:42.500 --> 00:06:49.200
 So let's take a look at this in C, which is a lot more like assembly language.

00:06:49.200 --> 00:06:54.600
 So if we take a look at the top of this, we include the standard I/O and we have a main program.

00:06:54.600 --> 00:06:58.500
 And we use the register, register int xr ACC.

00:06:58.500 --> 00:07:03.500
 Now, for those of you who don't know C, the register is a keyword in the C language.

00:07:03.500 --> 00:07:08.100
 And it says, this is going to be something that I'm going to want to make high performance.

00:07:08.100 --> 00:07:11.300
 So put it in a register if you possibly can.

00:07:11.300 --> 00:07:15.000
 Then I'm going to create a character array named mem.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:24.900
 Now, this is going to be a six-character array with a zero termination, the letters hello followed by a zero.

00:07:24.900 --> 00:07:31.900
 And so then what we're saying is we're saying for xr equals zero, as long as mem sub xr,

00:07:31.900 --> 00:07:40.600
 we're now looking for that zero terminated string, as long as mem xr is non-zero, continue and then add one to xr.

00:07:40.600 --> 00:07:46.800
 So then we take our, that's our index variable, our loop iteration variable.

00:07:46.800 --> 00:07:53.900
 So we say, oh, let's take the accumulator and load in mem sub xr because xr is our sort of index variable.

00:07:53.900 --> 00:07:58.000
 And in this case, we're dealing with ASCII and we know it.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:02.600
 So if the accumulator minus a is less than zero, we continue.

00:08:02.600 --> 00:08:10.600
 And if you recall and see the continue does mean that the increment part of the for loop is executed. So xr plus plus.

00:08:10.600 --> 00:08:17.700
 If not, we're going to say mem x sub xr equals the accumulator minus zero x20.

00:08:17.700 --> 00:08:22.200
 So we're doing the case conversion there and putting it right back into mem xr.

00:08:22.200 --> 00:08:28.200
 That for loops runs five times and then we print out the uppercase.

00:08:28.200 --> 00:08:34.500
 So now we are going to finally walk through the assembly language version of this.

00:08:34.500 --> 00:08:40.000
 So I've got the code on the left and I've got the before memory and the after memory on the right.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:44.400
 Now, one of the things that you'll notice is that I have given you on the right hand side,

00:08:44.400 --> 00:08:50.800
 I've given you the sort of pseudo code for the C code that corresponds to the assembly language that we're going to do.

00:08:50.800 --> 00:08:57.400
 So we're going to effectively construct a for loop that's going to loop through an array of characters.

00:08:57.400 --> 00:09:01.000
 So the first thing we do is we're going to set x to zero, clear x.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:05.700
 And then we're going to have a label to come back up to the top of our for loop.

00:09:05.700 --> 00:09:12.600
 The next instruction, lda $00, x, is the new instruction we haven't used so far.

00:09:12.600 --> 00:09:16.400
 And this is an index load into the accumulator.

00:09:16.400 --> 00:09:20.900
 $00 is the starting address and the x register contains our offset.

00:09:20.900 --> 00:09:26.400
 So it basically adds x to wherever we're at and then that becomes the address.

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:29.600
 And then we're going to load that into the accumulator.

00:09:29.600 --> 00:09:38.100
 Now, that act of loading into the accumulator is going to set the z flag and the n flag as any change to any register does.

00:09:38.100 --> 00:09:41.900
 And so we're going to use a BEQ, which is really kind of branch zero.

00:09:41.900 --> 00:09:46.500
 That means if the accumulator is zero, we're going to follow the branch.

00:09:46.500 --> 00:09:52.800
 But in this case, the accumulator is going to have uppercase H, 0x48.

00:09:52.800 --> 00:09:56.500
 And so BEQ is not going to branch, so we're going to fall through.

00:09:56.500 --> 00:09:58.900
 And then we're going to start our if test in a sense.

00:09:58.900 --> 00:10:04.000
 Compare the accumulator to lowercase a.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:12.500
 Now, recall that in ASCII, uppercase a is less than lowercase a in the ASCII chart.

00:10:12.500 --> 00:10:19.000
 So if it's already uppercase, that comparison is going to be minus, right?

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:21.200
 It's going to be negative.

00:10:21.200 --> 00:10:27.500
 And so we're going to branch to, in effect, a label that I called cont, which is sort of like a continue.

00:10:27.500 --> 00:10:33.700
 So we're going to skip the subtract if it's already an uppercase.

00:10:33.700 --> 00:10:39.000
 So BMI cont skips the subtraction if it's already uppercase.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:41.700
 Then we come into the continue label.

00:10:41.700 --> 00:10:44.500
 And then we are incrementing x.

00:10:44.500 --> 00:10:48.900
 Now, remember that continue actually runs the increment of a for loop.

00:10:48.900 --> 00:10:53.700
 And then we're going to jump back up to the top of the loop.

00:10:53.700 --> 00:10:55.700
 But x is now 1.

00:10:55.700 --> 00:11:04.100
 And now we're going to load index load from at location 0 with x of 1.

00:11:04.100 --> 00:11:10.800
 And so now we get the 0x65, which is the lowercase e.

00:11:10.800 --> 00:11:13.500
 And we're going to check to see if we're out of the loop or not.

00:11:13.500 --> 00:11:14.200
 We're going to fall through.

00:11:14.200 --> 00:11:19.700
 We're going to compare the lowercase e to lowercase a.

00:11:19.700 --> 00:11:25.700
 And in this case, it's not minus because e is greater than a.

00:11:25.700 --> 00:11:27.000
 And so we're going to do the subtraction.

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:32.000
 So we're going to convert that to uppercase by subtracting 20 hex.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:39.500
 And then we're going to store it right back into that location, which is location 0 indexed by the x register, which is 1.

00:11:39.500 --> 00:11:44.000
 And so that's going to put 0x45 into location 1.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:45.400
 Then we drop into the continue.

00:11:45.400 --> 00:11:47.100
 We add 1 to x.

00:11:47.100 --> 00:11:48.300
 The x register becomes 2.

00:11:48.300 --> 00:11:50.000
 And we jump to the top of the loop.

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:52.300
 So you see how this is kind of working, right?

00:11:52.300 --> 00:11:55.000
 So now x is 2.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:12:02.100
 And so we do an indexed load of location 0 plus 2.

00:12:02.100 --> 00:12:03.500
 Branch if it's equal to done.

00:12:03.500 --> 00:12:07.300
 Check to see if it's uppercase already.

00:12:07.300 --> 00:12:08.600
 And in this case, it's not.

00:12:08.600 --> 00:12:09.800
 So we subtract.

00:12:09.800 --> 00:12:11.800
 So at some point, you can follow this.

00:12:11.800 --> 00:12:17.700
 It will go round and round until we get to an offset of 5.

00:12:17.700 --> 00:12:19.000
 Jump to the top of the loop.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:24.400
 We're going to load location 0 plus x, which is 5.

00:12:24.400 --> 00:12:26.100
 And in this case, it's going to be a 0.

00:12:26.100 --> 00:12:29.500
 And then the BEQ is going to be true in a sense.

00:12:29.500 --> 00:12:31.600
 And then we're going to jump to done.

00:12:31.600 --> 00:12:40.300
 And then the application is going to finish and print out its after data, which is fully uppercased.

00:12:40.300 --> 00:12:41.000
 Hello.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:44.500
 That's a bunch of assembly language and C and Python.

00:12:44.500 --> 00:12:47.800
 And I would say that you're going to spend a bunch of time with the emulator

00:12:47.800 --> 00:12:50.800
 and a bunch of time with the emulator documentation.

00:12:50.800 --> 00:12:55.700
 And hopefully, with some time, this will all make sense to you.

